[2] Cholera, Gastroenteritis - India (Gujarat)
Date: Tue, 24 May 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: ExpressIndia.com [edited]
<http://cities.expressindia.com/fullstory.php?newsid=130893>


120 hospitalized, 2 test cholera-positive
-----------------------------------------
Panic struck residents of Vadodara city on Tuesday morning, 24 May
2005, as reports of a cholera epidemic spread. Over 120 people from
different parts of the city were admitted to various hospitals since
the previous night. Latest reports said that 2 of the patients
admitted to Infectious Disease Hospital tested positive to cholera. A
15-year-old from Roshan Nagar and a 32-year-old from Madanzampa were
declared to be cholera-affected.

Authorities at SSG Hospital confirm that all the 16 children admitted
there were victims of gastroenteritis. "The disease has spread
through water.However, all the patients are stable," said S Binjoo,
Resident Medical Officer (RMO). People from Panigate, Hathikhana,
Fatehpura, Yakubpura and Wadi were rushed to hospitals after they
fell ill. Those admitted to SSG Hospital came from these areas.

The influx of patients began around 10 pm, 23 May 2005, when several
residents in Hathikhana, especially children, were rushed to
hospitals with vomiting and dysentery symptoms. Patients kept coming
in until 4 am the following day. "It was chaos throughout the night
here. People carrying children and patients were using private
vehicles to rush to nearest hospitals," said a resident of Mahavat
Phadia, Hathikhana. His 2 children were admitted to Jamnabhai
Hospital.

"A group of people reportedly attended a wedding in Hathikhana where
they may have been affected by food poisoning. However, several cases
were from individual pockets in different regions and hence it is too
early to say what caused the illness," said Dr Pragnya Joshi, Civil
Surgeon, Jamnabhai Hospital, which had got the maximum number of
cases - 107. The hospital has got 78 cases from Hathikhana, 11 from
Panigate, 7 from Fatehpura, 7 from Yakubpura and 4 from Wadi.

"2 cases admitted to ID Hospital were confirmed as cholera. We have
collected water samples from the affected areas and are trying to
know why the epidemic spread," said Deepikaben Janak Kumar Thakkar,
Chairman of the VMC Health Committee.

--
