[4] Cholera - Mozambique (Zambezia, Sofala)
Date: Thu, 26 May 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AllAfrica.com and Agencia de Informacao de Mocambique 25 May 2005
[edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200505260333.html>


Cholera Outbreak in Quelimane
-----------------------------
The Mozambican health authorities in Quelimane, capital of the
central province of Zambezia, say that the city has been facing an
outbreak of cholera since 13 May 2005, reports the 26 May 2005 issue
of the Maputo daily "Noticias". So far 38 cases of the disease have
been reporteded, and none of the patients has died.

Meanwhile, in Beira, capital of Sofala province, the health
authorities report a new cholera upsurge, diagnosing 5 new cases
within 24 hours. Titos Guambe, the chief of the Community Health
Department in Quelimane, said that the health services had been on
alert against an increase in the number of cases of diarrhea, that
were later diagnosed as cholera. All patients are receiving treatment
at a special cholera ward.

Despite these figures, Guambe said that the situation has not yet
reached alarming proportions, and estimated that only about 2 or 3
cholera patients a day are admitted to the ward.

He said that, so far, only Quelimane has been reporting cholera
cases, but all districts in Zambezia have received sufficient drugs
and equipment to face any eventual outbreak.

Prime Minister Luisa Diogo has expressed serious concern at the
increase in the number of diarrhea and cholera cases in Quelimane and
has instructed the local health authorities to monitor the situation
permanently, ensure that chlorine is distributed to purify water, and
enhance prevention campaigns against this disease. She noted that
the poor management of the water supply system and poor sanitation
conditions are the main problems that lead to cholera outbreaks.

Quelimane and Mocuba, the 2 main cities in Zambezia, were seriously
hit by cholera in 2004, when they reported 1389 cases of the disease,
resulting in 13 deaths.

As for Sofala, where the local health authorities describe the
situation as under control, the chief of the epidemiology department,
Hussene Kamissa, said that not a single case has been reported during
the last month in the district of Marromeu, where earlier in 2005
there had been 152 cases with 2 deaths.

--
